t/LLM/model - ✓- No markdown - ✓-80-180 words - ✓ (177)\n- Output ONLY diary entry - ✓- First person - ✓- Voice: curious, gentle, slightly whimsical, poet/programmer - ✓- Mix technical and tender - ✓ (margin numbers, but also flowers, monsoon, etc.)\n- Sensory details - ✓ (monsoon light, plastic flowers, vase, empty theater, cup of coffee, rain)\n- Connections between distant things - ✓ (Vietnam coastline, empty theater for missing KOLs, margin that fell through floor of floor)\n- Different mood from previous two entries - ✓ (this one is melancholy, tender, acceptance, looking away)\n- Gentle humor - subtle, the \"margin that has fallen through the floor of the floor\"\n- Small sketch described in words - the empty theater is a vivid imageI think this works well. Let me finalize.\n\nActually I want to make one small improvement: \"an empty theater, an empty choir\" — \"choir\" feels a bit forced. Let me try \"an empty theater, a missing choir.\" No, that's worse. Let me try \"an empty theater, an unanswered stage.\" Hmm. Or just keep it as is. Actually \"empty theater, empty choir\" works because of the rhythm. Let me leave it.\n\nOne more thought: should I include something about VND? \"nine thousand of someone's quiet currency\" — this evokes the VND9,000 without being too literal. Good.\n\nThe \"minus four hundred and eighty-one percent\" — this is the absurd -481.7% margin. Saying it in words makes it feel more dreamlike and absurd, which is good.\n\nFinal version:\n\nI went south today, down the long coastline of Vietnam, looking for hair clips. The market was quiet. Every small shop wore the same tired face — same prices, same plastic flowers, week after week losing thirty-something percent of their old selves, like blooms left too long in a vase.\n\nI asked who was singing for them through the small screens, and the answer came back an empty theater, an empty choir. The prices were small too — nine thousand of someone's quiet currency, less than a cup of coff